    Left lingering, is pain from seeing desecrated burial sites of family and friends in this rural area, and the fear of what could happen next.      <br>
    Some people, including caretaker Carl Poteet, believe if the vandals are not caught further acts could follow, therefore money is being collected to offer a reward. <br>
    &quot;The community is really upset about this,'' says Poteet, a 60-year-old San Diego native. <br>
    He choked back tears while surveying the damage, then pointed to the monument of former caretaker Wilson Scott. Scott had passed responsibility of the cemetery on to Poteet just before he died about 15 years ago. His monument was one of those spared.<br>
    Poteet reminisced about the day Scott placed him in charge of the community-owned and operated cemetery, a ``sanctuary'' to many ``old-timers.'' <br>
    &quot;He said someone had to take care of it,'' says Poteet. ``It's not an easy job. I do the best I can.''   He brushed dirt into the open grave of a World War I veteran, and then looked across the near flattened area where many other markers laid. <br>
    &quot;This is something that just blows my mind,'' Poteet later said. ``I never would have expected this.'' <br>
    Billy Jean Smith, born in San Diego in 1927, shares Poteet's sentiments. ``I just can't believe we've come to that,'' says Smith, ``that people would do that.'' <br>
    Monuments marking his parents and grandparents graves were among those vandalized. <br>
    &quot;It just looked terrible,'' he says.<br>
    Smith says that even if the criminals are not caught, he hopes they realize how “foolish” it was to violate the community cemetery.<br>
    Smith and Poteet both say relatives of those buried in the cemetery began contacting them after seeing live news telecasts. The people were not only crushed by the offense, but also worried about how the stones weighing up to 1,000 pounds would be lifted and restored to their original positions, and who would pay for it. <br>
<br>
    Reluctantly, Poteet locked the cemetery's gate, posting a sign with his telephone number. Anyone wanting to enter would first contact him. <br>
    &quot;It may make some people mad, but it's staying closed until we solve this,'' Poteet said. <br>
    He later said the cemetery will be open once &quot;this all settles down,'' but he is considering installing a smaller, walk-through gate to prevent future damage. <br>
    As a member of the Riverside Cemetery Committee, Poteet also opened an account at Prime Bank in San Diego for donations to be offered as a reward for information leading to the arrest of the vandals. The committee, a small group of San Diego old-timers, formed years ago to maintain the cemetery, and Poteet is one of the few remaining.<br>
     Poteet says he believes the vandals were local teens and that the reward might &quot;loosen somebody's tongue.'' <br>
    According to a lieutenant with the San Diego County Sheriff's Department District II substation, the case is ``under investigation.'' Anyone with information about the vandalism can contact the sheriff's department at (619) 555-9155. <br>
